00:39:57.754 --> 00:39:58.420
Other questions?

00:40:01.510 --> 00:40:04.020
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I have
a question about-- I

00:40:04.020 --> 00:40:06.980
like your comments about
connectedness in the world,

00:40:06.980 --> 00:40:07.650
right?

00:40:07.650 --> 00:40:10.370
And to some degree,
I think you expressed

00:40:10.370 --> 00:40:13.540
maybe some disappointment
about how even

00:40:13.540 --> 00:40:15.550
the connections that
there are internationally,

00:40:15.550 --> 00:40:18.020
that they are sort of obvious
to some degree, right?

00:40:18.020 --> 00:40:21.260
Me as a German, I might be more
connected to other Germans,

00:40:21.260 --> 00:40:23.890
so these connections are worth
less to some degree, right?

00:40:27.294 --> 00:40:29.710
I wonder if we have enough
tools for these kind of things.

00:40:29.710 --> 00:40:32.272
Like I mean, you mentioned like
the cafeteria model, right?

00:40:32.272 --> 00:40:33.730
You go into a
cafeteria and you sit

00:40:33.730 --> 00:40:38.460
next to people that are
similar to yourself, right?

00:40:38.460 --> 00:40:40.860
And I think in social
networks, it always

00:40:40.860 --> 00:40:43.190
tends to be that all the
new connection you make

00:40:43.190 --> 00:40:45.677
are obvious given the kind
of things you do, right?

00:40:45.677 --> 00:40:47.260
You travel to a
remote office and then

00:40:47.260 --> 00:40:49.593
maybe you get connected to
people in that remote office,

00:40:49.593 --> 00:40:50.580
right?

00:40:50.580 --> 00:40:52.160
Do you know if
there's any good tools

00:40:52.160 --> 00:40:54.810
to get randomly
connected, like sort

00:40:54.810 --> 00:40:57.200
of like a sort of
virtual cocktail hours,

00:40:57.200 --> 00:40:59.860
where you just socialize with
completely random people that

00:40:59.860 --> 00:41:02.280
also are interested
in socializing

00:41:02.280 --> 00:41:03.892
with other completely
random people?

00:41:03.892 --> 00:41:06.350
ETHAN ZUCKERMAN: So there's
two approaches to this problem.

00:41:06.350 --> 00:41:10.740
There are people who've
done pure randomness.

00:41:10.740 --> 00:41:14.336
And pure randomness doesn't
work necessarily all that well.

00:41:14.336 --> 00:41:15.710
To a certain
extent, Chatroulette

00:41:15.710 --> 00:41:17.870
is pure randomness, right?

00:41:17.870 --> 00:41:19.560
That was kind of the
theory behind it.

00:41:19.560 --> 00:41:21.530
Let's just open a chat
window, someone else

00:41:21.530 --> 00:41:22.740
arbitrarily in the room.

00:41:22.740 --> 00:41:24.770
The emergence of
the social norms of,

00:41:24.770 --> 00:41:28.500
and now let me show you my
genitals, was sort of emergent

00:41:28.500 --> 00:41:29.560
on top of that platform.

00:41:29.560 --> 00:41:31.851
But that may simply
be where you end up

00:41:31.851 --> 00:41:33.850
when you're dealing with
sort of pure randomness

00:41:33.850 --> 00:41:36.109
and pure anonymity.

00:41:36.109 --> 00:41:37.650
And there are people
playing with it.

00:41:37.650 --> 00:41:40.050
And then there are
services like StumbleUpon

00:41:40.050 --> 00:41:44.640
that are sort of trying
almost pure random.

00:41:44.640 --> 00:41:47.700
There's an app called
Random that works on this.

00:41:47.700 --> 00:41:50.230
The ones that I'm actually
much more interested in

00:41:50.230 --> 00:41:52.660
are trying to
engineer serendipity.

00:41:52.660 --> 00:41:55.970
And they're looking
for a connection

00:41:55.970 --> 00:41:59.530
where some aspect of it
is something in common,

00:41:59.530 --> 00:42:02.600
and some aspect of it
is something unexpected.

00:42:02.600 --> 00:42:05.780
So two really quick
models on this.

00:42:05.780 --> 00:42:10.320
Like a lot of people, like a lot
of geeks my age, I miss Usenet.

00:42:10.320 --> 00:42:13.420
And I miss sort of
the early '90s Usenet.

00:42:13.420 --> 00:42:16.250
And what I specifically miss
about the early '90s Usenet

00:42:16.250 --> 00:42:19.610
was that it was a
topic-organized internet.

00:42:19.610 --> 00:42:23.364
So if I found
myself on rec.photo,

00:42:23.364 --> 00:42:24.780
there was a good
chance that I was

00:42:24.780 --> 00:42:27.530
going to run into someone from
Japan or someone from Finland,

00:42:27.530 --> 00:42:30.990
but we were going to have
enough in common round emergent

00:42:30.990 --> 00:42:33.510
digital photography that
we would have a reason

00:42:33.510 --> 00:42:34.950
to have a conversation.

00:42:34.950 --> 00:42:38.261
And then we might have more
of that geographic diversity,

00:42:38.261 --> 00:42:40.510
maybe more of the gender
diversity, more of the income

00:42:40.510 --> 00:42:44.660
diversity coming from
having that topic in common.

00:42:44.660 --> 00:42:46.550
Where I'm now sort of
thinking about this

00:42:46.550 --> 00:42:49.180
is I actually think
Twitter is potentially

00:42:49.180 --> 00:42:50.690
a very interesting
tool for this.

00:42:50.690 --> 00:42:52.660
Because the connection
is pretty lightweight.

00:42:52.660 --> 00:42:54.650
You're sort of
sharing information.

00:42:54.650 --> 00:42:57.233
And so part of what I'm trying
to do-- one of the things we're

00:42:57.233 --> 00:42:58.730
playing around
with right now is,

00:42:58.730 --> 00:43:02.400
can I try to figure out what
your community of interests

00:43:02.400 --> 00:43:03.860
looks like on Twitter?

00:43:03.860 --> 00:43:07.630
And can I find a community that
is related but sufficiently

00:43:07.630 --> 00:43:08.510
different?

00:43:08.510 --> 00:43:10.870
So if I'm a social media
guru or whatever the hell

00:43:10.870 --> 00:43:15.330
that means in the US, can I
find that person in Nigeria?

00:43:15.330 --> 00:43:18.140
And in having that
element of difference

00:43:18.140 --> 00:43:20.170
as well as that
element of similarity,

00:43:20.170 --> 00:43:22.310
can there be enough that
we're likely to have

00:43:22.310 --> 00:43:24.032
that really
profitable connection,

00:43:24.032 --> 00:43:25.990
but enough difference
that we're likely to have

00:43:25.990 --> 00:43:27.180
something else of it?

00:43:27.180 --> 00:43:29.870
It's a really hard problem.

00:43:29.870 --> 00:43:32.380
And in doing sort of reading
recommendation around it,

00:43:32.380 --> 00:43:34.004
which is what Catherine
D'Ignazio and I

00:43:34.004 --> 00:43:37.670
spent a lot of time doing on
that Terra Incognita problem.

00:43:37.670 --> 00:43:42.090
We actually figured out that
it's probably not as simple as

00:43:42.090 --> 00:43:44.060
hi, have a chat.

00:43:44.060 --> 00:43:47.300
It's probably more like, can
I give you enough information

00:43:47.300 --> 00:43:50.290
that you would have something
to have a chat about?

00:43:50.290 --> 00:43:52.020
And so the model
that I'm in some ways

00:43:52.020 --> 00:43:55.100
really interested in is one
that started in Scandinavia,

00:43:55.100 --> 00:43:57.430
is now sort of playing out
in public libraries, which

00:43:57.430 --> 00:44:02.460
is the human library, which is
you identify a set of people

00:44:02.460 --> 00:44:03.970
from very different
walks of life,

00:44:03.970 --> 00:44:05.407
very different backgrounds.

00:44:05.407 --> 00:44:07.490
You put them in the library,
and you offer someone

00:44:07.490 --> 00:44:09.820
the opportunity to
go check out a person

00:44:09.820 --> 00:44:11.210
and sort of have a conversation.

00:44:11.210 --> 00:44:14.160
And whenever this has
been done at libraries,

00:44:14.160 --> 00:44:16.246
it sort of sells out
almost immediately.

00:44:16.246 --> 00:44:17.870
My wife and I were
sort of arguing over

00:44:17.870 --> 00:44:20.315
who got to do it at Williams
College in Williamstown,

00:44:20.315 --> 00:44:24.120
and we figured that random
professorial type was not

00:44:24.120 --> 00:44:26.330
as appealing as rabbi,
which was her identity.

00:44:26.330 --> 00:44:29.620
And so she signed up as
a rabbi and had like 9

00:44:29.620 --> 00:44:31.670
of her 10 slots filled
almost immediately.

00:44:31.670 --> 00:44:35.020
The one guy who was more
popular out in deep blue Western

00:44:35.020 --> 00:44:37.680
Massachusetts was Gun Owner.

00:44:37.680 --> 00:44:39.990
And everyone wanted to
go talk to this guy.

00:44:39.990 --> 00:44:42.480
And I'm now actually taking
shooting lessons from the guy.

00:44:42.480 --> 00:44:44.890
So there are really
interesting things

00:44:44.890 --> 00:44:48.040
that sort of happen when
you set up structures

00:44:48.040 --> 00:44:49.375
to allow people to meet.

00:44:49.375 --> 00:44:50.250
But I agree with you.

00:44:50.250 --> 00:44:51.390
I think in many
cases, it's something

00:44:51.390 --> 00:44:53.140
where we would want
to do a lot more work.

00:44:53.140 --> 00:44:54.190
