00:44:54.190 --> 00:44:58.510
AUDIENCE: This is sort
of a modeled question,

00:44:58.510 --> 00:45:02.800
but I think-- well, my
viewpoint anyway-- we

00:45:02.800 --> 00:45:06.730
have a bit of a problem with
this partisan echo chamber.

00:45:06.730 --> 00:45:09.840
You can select news
sources that are never

00:45:09.840 --> 00:45:15.790
going to deliver you information
that challenges your worldview.

00:45:15.790 --> 00:45:20.970
But if I go look for
information sources

00:45:20.970 --> 00:45:27.360
that are not from my
partisan perspective,

00:45:27.360 --> 00:45:29.270
I wind up reading op
eds that sort of make

00:45:29.270 --> 00:45:32.110
me want to throw a brick
through my computer screen.

00:45:32.110 --> 00:45:35.950
And I don't know-- do you have
any thoughts on if there's

00:45:35.950 --> 00:45:43.870
a way out of this trap of
you want information that

00:45:43.870 --> 00:45:48.470
challenges you, but you don't
want information or opinion,

00:45:48.470 --> 00:45:51.184
maybe, that is repugnant.

00:45:51.184 --> 00:45:53.100
ETHAN ZUCKERMAN: I think
that's exactly right,

00:45:53.100 --> 00:45:55.090
and by the way, not
a muddled question,

00:45:55.090 --> 00:45:59.500
a nicely put question and right
at the heart of some really

00:45:59.500 --> 00:46:01.600
interesting debates
going on in the space.

00:46:01.600 --> 00:46:04.830
There's a huge
debate going on about

00:46:04.830 --> 00:46:09.530
whether the internet is
separating us politically.

00:46:09.530 --> 00:46:11.950
And I would say on one side,
probably the best articulated

00:46:11.950 --> 00:46:15.130
is a guy named Cass
Sunstein, who has said,

00:46:15.130 --> 00:46:18.640
I've done experiments
in deliberation.

00:46:18.640 --> 00:46:21.300
You put people in the room
with like-minded people,

00:46:21.300 --> 00:46:22.820
people get more extreme.

00:46:22.820 --> 00:46:25.280
If I hang out with the far
left, I get further left.

00:46:25.280 --> 00:46:28.850
You hang out with the far
right, you get further right.

00:46:28.850 --> 00:46:32.805
Gentzkow and Shapiro, really
pair of economists at Chicago,

00:46:32.805 --> 00:46:34.180
wrote a paper
essentially saying,

00:46:34.180 --> 00:46:36.000
no, no, no, the
internet's actually

00:46:36.000 --> 00:46:39.330
much better than the
rest of the media.

00:46:39.330 --> 00:46:41.810
You're actually going to
get more diverse audiences.

00:46:41.810 --> 00:46:43.440
It's a really
controversial paper.

00:46:43.440 --> 00:46:45.950
I take it on at some
length in the book

00:46:45.950 --> 00:46:48.350
and come to a different
conclusion than they come to.

00:46:48.350 --> 00:46:50.070
But they're better
economists than I am,

00:46:50.070 --> 00:46:51.320
so they may be right.

00:46:51.320 --> 00:46:52.620
I may be wrong.

00:46:52.620 --> 00:46:56.070
My take on this would
be the first instinct,

00:46:56.070 --> 00:46:59.077
which is, OK, let
me turn on Fox News,

00:46:59.077 --> 00:47:01.410
and I'm going to understand
what they're thinking about,

00:47:01.410 --> 00:47:03.600
is probably wrong.

00:47:03.600 --> 00:47:07.771
Because you're going to the
absolute opposite pole of where

00:47:07.771 --> 00:47:08.270
you are.

00:47:08.270 --> 00:47:10.160
And it's really hard
to look at this other

00:47:10.160 --> 00:47:13.630
than, that's the enemy, I want
to figure out who they are,

00:47:13.630 --> 00:47:14.955
and I want to undercut them.

00:47:14.955 --> 00:47:17.350
I actually think
the thing to do is,

00:47:17.350 --> 00:47:19.210
when you're sort of
orthogonal with someone,

00:47:19.210 --> 00:47:22.895
to try to figure out how you
get the optimum sort of angle

00:47:22.895 --> 00:47:24.580
of consonance, right?

00:47:24.580 --> 00:47:30.590
So if I'm looking for a
conservative viewpoint

00:47:30.590 --> 00:47:33.310
that I might want to
pay real attention to,

00:47:33.310 --> 00:47:35.960
I'm not going to
look for someone

00:47:35.960 --> 00:47:38.560
who's contemptuous of
science and someone who's

00:47:38.560 --> 00:47:41.440
deeply religious and someone
who's from the American South.

00:47:41.440 --> 00:47:43.850
What I might end
up looking for is

00:47:43.850 --> 00:47:47.180
someone who is also from New
England, also in academia,

00:47:47.180 --> 00:47:51.220
but happens to think really
different things than I do.

00:47:51.220 --> 00:47:53.260
And when I'm able to
find those people,

00:47:53.260 --> 00:47:55.960
I find myself much
more challenged.

00:47:55.960 --> 00:47:58.380
And so that may only be a
15 degrees of difference

00:47:58.380 --> 00:48:00.335
rather than 180
degrees of difference,

00:48:00.335 --> 00:48:01.710
but that 15 degrees
of difference

00:48:01.710 --> 00:48:03.251
puts me in a place
where I'm actually

00:48:03.251 --> 00:48:06.660
forced to deal with the argument
and sort of read it through.

00:48:06.660 --> 00:48:08.520
And so what I'm
interested in is,

00:48:08.520 --> 00:48:12.000
can we start identifying those
people 15 to 30 degrees off

00:48:12.000 --> 00:48:14.841
of where we are, and then
find out what they read,

00:48:14.841 --> 00:48:16.590
and find out how we
meet them, and sort of

00:48:16.590 --> 00:48:19.100
find out how we sort of
have those conversations?

00:48:19.100 --> 00:48:21.350
These are the sorts of
systems that I would really

00:48:21.350 --> 00:48:23.722
like to be building.

00:48:23.722 --> 00:48:25.930
But I've only got sort of
three or four grad students

00:48:25.930 --> 00:48:26.600
over there.

00:48:26.600 --> 00:48:29.802
And this is a big company.

00:48:29.802 --> 00:48:31.510
You guys build a lot
of different things.

00:48:31.510 --> 00:48:34.620
I'm really interested in,
can I get other people

00:48:34.620 --> 00:48:37.460
in the tech industry who
are interested in exactly

00:48:37.460 --> 00:48:40.770
that question that you're
asking to sort of say,

00:48:40.770 --> 00:48:43.900
is this perhaps part
of our responsibility?

00:48:43.900 --> 00:48:45.610
Is this part of
what we should be

00:48:45.610 --> 00:48:50.180
asking our tools to do, is
not just give us what we want,

00:48:50.180 --> 00:48:54.110
but possibly giving us
what we need in civic terms

00:48:54.110 --> 00:48:57.490
to try to get to a more
inclusive society in one

00:48:57.490 --> 00:49:00.160
fashion or another?

00:49:00.160 --> 00:49:02.350
Anybody else?

00:49:02.350 --> 00:49:03.250
Hey.

00:49:03.250 --> 00:49:04.120
AUDIENCE: Hello.

00:49:04.120 --> 00:49:07.320
So people listening to this
talk who may be very interested,

00:49:07.320 --> 00:49:09.270
but they're working
on another project,

00:49:09.270 --> 00:49:12.490
and a few months pass,
and they forget about it--

00:49:12.490 --> 00:49:16.650
how can we foster a more
frequent contact so that this

00:49:16.650 --> 00:49:17.900
stays on people's minds?

00:49:17.900 --> 00:49:19.850
ETHAN ZUCKERMAN: Well,
I am across the street.

00:49:19.850 --> 00:49:20.870
And you can come see us.

00:49:20.870 --> 00:49:22.150
And you can actually
get into to my building

00:49:22.150 --> 00:49:23.680
without ID, which
is always nice.

00:49:23.680 --> 00:49:30.220
But so a couple things--
I sort of soft-pedaled

00:49:30.220 --> 00:49:31.730
the Global Voices project.

00:49:31.730 --> 00:49:36.500
But there's actually a very
vibrant community of people

00:49:36.500 --> 00:49:38.800
around that really working
on this question of,

00:49:38.800 --> 00:49:40.675
how would you pay more
attention to the world

00:49:40.675 --> 00:49:43.240
and sort of how would you
fight the way in which

00:49:43.240 --> 00:49:45.330
those countries are
framed and understood?

00:49:45.330 --> 00:49:47.330
And so one of the things
that I would definitely

00:49:47.330 --> 00:49:49.990
encourage people to
do is to think about,

00:49:49.990 --> 00:49:52.790
is that something
to connect with?

00:49:52.790 --> 00:49:55.230
We are doing some
active experiments

00:49:55.230 --> 00:49:57.150
on trying to figure
out both, can we

00:49:57.150 --> 00:50:01.830
monitor media consumption
voluntarily, sort of opt in?

00:50:01.830 --> 00:50:04.470
And when we learn that
media consumption has

00:50:04.470 --> 00:50:05.960
certain biases
associated with it,

00:50:05.960 --> 00:50:09.160
can we do structured
recommendations of content?

00:50:09.160 --> 00:50:12.560
And for me, that strikes me
as a very interesting place--

00:50:12.560 --> 00:50:13.670
potential to collaborate.

00:50:13.670 --> 00:50:15.800
And we do have students sort
of working on that and sort

00:50:15.800 --> 00:50:17.216
of playing with
that, and you guys

00:50:17.216 --> 00:50:19.667
would be very welcome to
come across the street

00:50:19.667 --> 00:50:21.625
to the Media Lab, have
conversations about that

00:50:21.625 --> 00:50:24.780
and sort of figure
out where to go.

00:50:24.780 --> 00:50:27.150
The trick in sort
of writing a book

00:50:27.150 --> 00:50:31.240
is you're trying
to identify people

00:50:31.240 --> 00:50:33.090
who think a problem
is important enough

00:50:33.090 --> 00:50:35.660
that they want to put
some time into it.

00:50:35.660 --> 00:50:40.630
And so this is sort
of my plea to people

00:50:40.630 --> 00:50:42.130
who think this is
interesting enough

00:50:42.130 --> 00:50:44.900
that they want to work on it.

00:50:44.900 --> 00:50:48.050
And I'm now sort of advising
half a dozen projects

00:50:48.050 --> 00:50:50.830
around the world
of people who think

00:50:50.830 --> 00:50:53.437
this is an interesting
thing to explore and want

00:50:53.437 --> 00:50:54.395
to work together on it.

00:50:54.395 --> 00:50:56.100
I would love to be
involved with sort

00:50:56.100 --> 00:50:57.469
of more of those conversations.

00:50:57.469 --> 00:51:00.010
I would also love to be involved
in conversations with people

00:51:00.010 --> 00:51:01.670
who I've got it
wrong and I'm not

00:51:01.670 --> 00:51:03.910
framing the question
the right way

00:51:03.910 --> 00:51:05.570
or the most provocative way.

00:51:05.570 --> 00:51:08.650
But I would hope to
sort of open a door

00:51:08.650 --> 00:51:12.390
around this, either to that
existing, thriving community

00:51:12.390 --> 00:51:15.017
around Global Voices or
to the nascent community

00:51:15.017 --> 00:51:17.100
around civic media that
we have across the street.

00:51:21.970 --> 00:51:22.470
Please.

00:51:22.470 --> 00:51:23.844
AUDIENCE: I think
also that might

00:51:23.844 --> 00:51:25.770
be a good opportunity
for the plug.

00:51:25.770 --> 00:51:29.130
If anybody here is interested
in sort of topics like citizen

00:51:29.130 --> 00:51:31.770
journalism and stuff like
that, we have a team here

00:51:31.770 --> 00:51:34.250
in Cambridge working on
YouTube live streaming,

00:51:34.250 --> 00:51:36.310
where we sort of
worry a lot about news

00:51:36.310 --> 00:51:40.250
and how live streaming of
news sort of can impact

00:51:40.250 --> 00:51:43.107
these kind of questions around
news and citizen journalism

00:51:43.107 --> 00:51:43.940
and stuff like that.

00:51:43.940 --> 00:51:46.660
And we're now starting work
with MIT Media Lab, actually.

00:51:46.660 --> 00:51:49.309
YouTube is funding research
at the MIT Media Lab

00:51:49.309 --> 00:51:50.600
to sort of explore these ideas.

00:51:50.600 --> 00:51:51.975
So we've been
actually in contact

00:51:51.975 --> 00:51:54.410
with Ethan, people who
are interested to work

00:51:54.410 --> 00:51:55.150
on these things.

00:51:55.150 --> 00:51:56.900
ETHAN ZUCKERMAN: And
precisely the project

00:51:56.900 --> 00:51:58.060
we're talking about
working on together

00:51:58.060 --> 00:51:59.960
is trying to figure
out, how do you put

00:51:59.960 --> 00:52:03.550
enough context around the
live stream of an event

00:52:03.550 --> 00:52:06.330
that it's comprehensible to
someone who doesn't know where

00:52:06.330 --> 00:52:08.150
it's coming from?

00:52:08.150 --> 00:52:09.780
I was looking at
this the other day,

00:52:09.780 --> 00:52:13.920
and the protests about the
internet tax in Hungary

00:52:13.920 --> 00:52:15.597
were being live-streamed
on YouTube.

00:52:15.597 --> 00:52:17.680
And on the one hand, this
was sort of fascinating.

00:52:17.680 --> 00:52:20.660
It's really interesting
to see tens of thousands

00:52:20.660 --> 00:52:23.930
of Hungarians come out into the
street over an internet access

00:52:23.930 --> 00:52:24.820
issue.

00:52:24.820 --> 00:52:28.080
The flip side is that my
Hungarian is not very good,

00:52:28.080 --> 00:52:30.970
and there's no
information or sort

00:52:30.970 --> 00:52:32.750
of context going on on that.

00:52:32.750 --> 00:52:34.700
How do we turn that
amazing ability

00:52:34.700 --> 00:52:37.790
we have to now be in
the streets of Budapest

00:52:37.790 --> 00:52:39.224
watching that protest unfold?

00:52:39.224 --> 00:52:40.890
How does that turn
into that opportunity

00:52:40.890 --> 00:52:42.480
to actually get informed on it?

00:52:42.480 --> 00:52:46.250
So we're excited to work
with you guys on that.

00:52:46.250 --> 00:52:47.440
Thank you so much, guys.

00:52:47.440 --> 00:52:48.750
Please help yourself to a book.

00:52:48.750 --> 00:52:51.440
I'm happy to sign one
if anyone is interested.

00:52:51.440 --> 00:52:54.120
I'm happy to sign more than
one if anyone is interested.

00:52:54.120 --> 00:52:55.850
It's been really
great to be here.

00:52:55.850 --> 00:52:59.200
[APPLAUSE]

